{"id":"1912.07499","submitter":"Axel Brandenburg","authors":"Axel Brandenburg and Stanislav Boldyrev","title":"The turbulent stress spectrum in the inertial and subinertial ranges","comments":"7 pages, 9 figures, ApJ, in press","journal-ref":"Astrophys. J. 892, 80 (2020)","doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/ab77bd","report-no":"Nordita-2019-133","categories":"astro-ph.CO astro-ph.GA physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For velocity and magnetic fields, the turbulent pressure and, more generally,\nthe squared fields such as the components of the turbulent stress tensor, play\nimportant roles in astrophysics. For both one and three dimensions, we derive\nthe equations relating the energy spectra of the fields to the spectra of their\nsquares. We solve the resulting integrals numerically and show that for\nturbulent energy spectra of Kolmogorov type, the spectral slope of the stress\nspectrum is also of Kolmogorov type. For shallower turbulence spectra, the\nslope of the stress spectrum quickly approaches that of white noise, regardless\nof how blue the spectrum of the field is. For fully helical fields, the stress\nspectrum is elevated by about a factor of two in the subinertial range, while\nthat in the inertial range remains unchanged. We discuss possible implications\nfor understanding the spectrum of primordial gravitational waves from causally\ngenerated magnetic fields during cosmological phase transitions in the early\nuniverse. We also discuss potential diagnostic applications to the interstellar\nmedium, where polarization and scintillation measurements characterize the\nsquare of the magnetic field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 16 Dec 2019 16:56:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 19 Feb 2020 19:24:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-01"}
