{"id":"1912.07876","submitter":"Guillaume Pignol","authors":"Guillaume Pignol","title":"A global perspective on searches for Electric Dipole Moments","comments":"Based on a talk given at IUPAP WG.9 Nuclear Science Symposium,\n  London, August 2019","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph hep-ex nucl-ex","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many experiments are underway in the world to search for a non-zero electric\ndipole moment (EDM) of a particle with spin 1/2 such as the neutron or the\nelectron. Finding an EDM would reveal new sources of CP violation. EDM\nmeasurements are motivated by the high sensitivity to new physics beyond the\nStandard Model. They are relevant to find the explanation for the\nmatter-antimatter asymmetry of the Universe. A variety of programs with\ndifferent systems are being pursued, with free neutrons, diamagnetic atoms,\nparamagnetic systems, and charged particles in storage rings. This article\npresents a basic introduction of the subject and attempts to compile the\nongoing projects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Dec 2019 08:50:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-18"}
